o address the consequences of industrialization and urbanization. By extending the reach of schools, broadening their mandate, and expanding their authority over the well-being of children, the state assumed a defining role in the education—and in the lives—of American families. In School, Society, and State, Steffes returns the state to the study of the history of education and brings the schools back into our discussion of state power during a pivotal moment in American political development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracy and educationxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aDemocracy and educationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducation and statexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aEducation and statezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducation, CompulsoryxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aEducation, CompulsoryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducational changexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aEducational changezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducational sociologyxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aEducational sociologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSchool management and organizationxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aSchool management and organizationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSchoolsxCentralizationxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aSchoolsxCentralizationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226772127423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226772127.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV